option.name: displayContent
option.value: what is -isystem arg used for

option.name: internalContent
option.value: what is -isystem arg used for

option.name: displayContent
option.value:
The `-isystem` argument is a flag used with the GCC and Clang compilers to specify directories that contain system header files. When you use `-isystem <directory>`, the compiler treats `<directory>` as a directory that contains system header files, and it adjusts its behavior accordingly:
1. **Warning Suppression**: The compiler will suppress warnings from headers found in the specified system directories. This is useful when including third-party libraries, as it keeps your build output cleaner and free from warnings that you cannot control.
2. **Include Order**: Headers specified with `-isystem` are searched after those specified with the `-I` or `-iquote` options but before the standard system directories. This helps in managing the order in which headers are included, especially when dealing with different versions of the same library.
### Usage Example
```sh g++ -isystem /path/to/system/headers myfile.cpp -o myfile ```
In this example, `/path/to/system/headers` is treated as a directory containing system headers and will suppress warnings coming from the files in that directory.
### Practical Context
In projects, you might see `-isystem` used in build configuration files such as Makefiles or CMakeLists.txt to handle third-party libraries without cluttering your warning messages:
**CMakeLists.txt:**
```cmake # Add system include directories include_directories(SYSTEM /path/to/system/headers) ```
**Makefile:**
```make # Add system include directories CPPFLAGS += -isystem /path/to/system/headers ```
This usage helps maintain a clean build environment while integrating dependencies smoothly.
